==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*fōtuz'', from Indo-European ''*pōd-'', lengthened ''o''-grade of ''*ped-'' ‘foot’.  Germanic cognates include Old Frisian ''fōt'', Old Saxon ''fōt'' (Dutch [[voet]]), Old High German [[fuoz]] (German [[Fuß]]), Old Norse [[fótr]] (Swedish [[fot#Swedish|fot]]), Gothic [[𐍆𐍉𐍄𐌿𐍃]].  The PIE root was also the source of Sanskrit [[पद्]], Greek [[πούς]] (gen. [[ποδός]]), Latin [[pes]] (gen. [[pedis]]).

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/fo:t/}}

===Noun===
{{Unicode|'''fōt'''}} ''m'' (plural {{Unicode|'''[[fet#Old English|fēt]]'''}})
# ''(Anatomy)''  A [[foot]]
# [[Pace]] or [[tread]]
# ''(Prosody)''  A [[foot]]
# A unit of length, especially as equal to a third of a [[yard]]

[[Category:Old English nouns]]

